com.camerontec.catalys.util.marketdata

Interface IInstrument

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Comparable<IInstrument>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    IFixMarketDataInstrument
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    FixMarketDataInstrument, StandardInstrument

    public interface IInstrument
extends Comparable<IInstrument>
    Represents an entity (eg a stock) that is traded on a market.

    Note that all prices are represented as whole numbers. Where a price has a fractional part, eg price is in dollars and cents, the value is the whole number of cents.

    Terminology:

    Top of book is defined as containing best buy and sell prices and quantities. Top of book data also normally includes the price and quantity of the last trade.

    Depth is defined as aggregated by price - there is only one entry per price level. Note that the top of book best buy and sell data is, by definition, the first buy and sell depth entries.

    Detail allows for multiple entries at the same price level. For example, each detail entry might represent a different broker's order in the market at that price level. Note that you should be able to compute depth from detail simply by adding up all the quantities from the detail entries at each price level.

    IInstruments can be compared to each other by their symbols.

      • getDepth

        IDepthEntry[] getDepth(boolean buy,
                       boolean removeEmptyEntries)
        Returns an array of IDepthEntry objects representing the depth of market on either the buy or sell side.
        Parameters:
        buy - Indicates whether you want the buy or sell side depth.
        removeEmptyEntries - If true, entries with 0 quantity are not returned in the array. It is usually more efficient to leave the zero entries in the array and ignore them. Otherwise a new array has to be created for each call.
        Returns:
        Array of IDepthEntry.

        Parameters:

        price - Price level of depth entry.
        Returns:

      • getImpliedPriceDecimalPlaces

        int getImpliedPriceDecimalPlaces()
        Returns the number of implied decimal places in a price for this instrument.

        For example, if prices for this instrument are quoted in dollars and cents, this method may return the value 2. This indicates that the int values returned by methods in this interface for prices have two implied decimal places. For example, a returned price of 125 indicates a price of 1.25.

        Returns:
        int The number of implied decimal places in returned prices for this instrument.

      • getInternalID

        int getInternalID()
        Returns unique int ID assigned to this instrument for the duration of this application (ie the life of the JVM).

        This ID is unique for every instrument object in this application. It is assigned automatically when the instrument is created. Note, however, that each time an application is launched, an instrument may be assigned a different ID.

        ID's start at 1 and increase incrementally - so it is practical to use this ID as an array index.

        It is useful within an application for quickly looking up instruments. It can be used as the basis of the standard equals and hashCode methods.

        Returns:
        Unique ID for this instrument. Always non zero positive.
